Lagos – Nigerian equities market continued on a downward trend yesterday with investors losing N23 billion. In summary, the ASI shed 62.19 absolute points, representing a decline of 0.15 per cent to close at 40,615.42 points. Also, the market capitalisation declined by N23 billion to close at N14.712 trillion. The downturn was impacted by losses recorded in medium and large capitalised stocks, amongst which are; Zenith Bank, FBN Holdings, Oando, Guaranty Trust Bank and Dangote Flour. Analysts at Afrinvest Limited said: “despite Monday’s bearish performance, we maintain our bullish outlook for the market hinged on the existence of bargain hunting opportunities in large and mid-cap stocks.” Market breadth closed negative, with 12 gainers versus 25 losers. Sovereign Trust Insurance recorded the highest price gain of five per cent, to close at 21 kobo per share. Continental Reinsurance gained 4.23 per cent to close at N1.48, while NPF Micro Finance Bank appreciated by 3.93 per cent to close at N1.85 per share. Wapic Insurance appreciated by 3.92 per cent  to close at 53 kobo, while Mutual Benefit Insurance gained 3.45 per cent to close at 30 kobo per share. On the other hand, Veritas Kapital Assurance led the losers’ chart by 9.52 per cent, to close at 38 kobo per share. Diamond Bank shed 9.39 per cent to close at N1.64, while Skye Bank depreciated by 5.56 per cent to close at 85 kobo per share. Japaul Oil declined by 5.41 per cent to close at 35 kobo and Cutix also shed 4.76 per cent to close at N3 per share. The total volume traded depreciated by 7.05 per cent to 203.36 million shares, worth N4.43 billion, and traded in 4,090 deals. Transactions in the shares of Guaranty Trust Bank topped the activity chart with 37.15 million shares valued at N1.64 billion. UBA followed with 31.46 million shares worth N361.1 million, while Fidelity Bank traded 14.5 million shares valued at N33.8 million. Zenith Bank traded 11.73 million shares valued at N330.46 million, while Oando tr